Reducing Gendered Disease Burden in Australia: Analysis and Findings from the Australian Burden of Disease Study

Daniel Fry

University of Sydney | Foundations of Data Analytics | April 2025

1 Brief

1.1 Client

The AIHW is an independent statutory Australian Government agency that produces authoritative and accessible information and statistics to inform and support better policy and service delivery decisions, leading to better health and wellbeing for all Australians. One of their major areas of responsibility is monitoring and reporting on chronic conditions, risk factors, and health outcomes.

This core responsibility is what this analysis relates to.

The client is interested in an exploration of how these different disease categories (and individual diseases if relevant) affect males and females, and what can be done to reduce the gendered disease burden of any such disease groups.

1.2 Core questions

  • Are there any disease categories that affect one sex significantly disproportionately? If so, investigate the causes of this.

  • Within these identified differences, are there any specific diseases that stand out as being singly or largely responsible for this gender disparity? What age groups are most affected? And what are the key risk factors that are contributing to this?

  • For the diseases that disproportionately affect one sex over another, what are the strongest associated risk factors that can be minimised to reduce this disparity, or reduce overall mortality.

2 Findings and Recommendations

2.1 Key Findings

  • There is gender disparity in mortality due to:

    • Infectious diseases - more deaths in men

    • Musculoskeletal conditions - more deaths in women

    • Neurological conditions - more deaths in women

    • Gastrointestinal conditions - more deaths in men

  • Main diseases responsible for these differences are:

    • Infectious diseases: HIV/AIDS, Hepatitis B, Hepatitis C

    • Musculoskeletal conditions: Rheumatoid and Osteoarthritis

    • Neurological conditions: Dementia and Alzheimers disease, multiple sclerosis

    • Gastrointestinal conditions: Chronic liver disease

Key risk factors relating to these diseases include:

  • 12% of deaths due to hepatitis B are attributable to unsafe injecting practices in men.

  • Being overweight combined with physical inactivity accounts for > 20% of female deaths due to dementia.

  • Alcohol use accounts for 27% of male deaths due to liver disease

2.2 Recommendations

  • Investment into alcohol abuse support systems for men would likely significantly reduce the disease burden of chronic liver disease.

  • Investment into safe and sterile injecting locations for drug users combined with greater investment into support for users of needle drugs will likely significantly reduce the disease burden of Hepatitis B.

  • Public health programs and incentives for women promoting physical activity combined with investment into mental health funding for women with disordered eating habits will likely reduce the disease burden of dementia.

  • Due to a link between hepatitis B and liver disease, investment into reducing the burden of hepatitis B will likely also indirectly reduce the disease burden of chronic liver disease.

joined_group_risk <- left_join(noage_riskxdis, groups_joining, by = c("cause_name" = "disease"))

joined_group_risk <- joined_group_risk %>%
  filter(data_year != 2024,  # 2024 is missing significant data

  mutate(risk_factor = as.factor(risk_factor),  # Ensure types are correct
         cause_name = as.factor(cause_name),
         sex = as.factor(sex),
         attributable_deaths = parse_number(attributable_deaths),

4.1 Plot

combined

Overwhelmingly, the leading causes of death in Australia in terms of overarching disease groups are cardiovascular diseases. This is distantly trailed by cancer and other neoplasms, and then this itself is distantly trailed by neurological conditions. Gender is significantly independent of disease group (Chi-squared test of independence: p = <0.0001), which allows for deeper analysis of the proportion plot on the right.

After filtering for disease groups which have greater than 1000 deaths over the study duration; the disease groups which have a disproportionate effect on one sex over the other are:

  • Infectious disease (~80% of deaths are male)

  • Neurological conditions (~65% of deaths are female)

  • Musculoskeletal disorders (~65% of deaths are female)

  • Gastrointenstinal disorders (~ 65% of deaths are male)

Of note are two disease groups: Infant and congenital conditions which disproportionately affect males but have a relatively small number of cases for diseases within the category, and blood and metabolic disorders which have significantly higher mortality for women, but a very low number of overall deaths. These two groups have been excluded on this basis.

The below table summarises this information:

proportion_table <- deaths1data %>%
  filter(!disease_group %in% c("Injury (external cause)", "Reproductive and maternal conditions", "Blood and metabolic disorders")) %>%
  group_by(disease_group, sex) %>%
  summarize(total_deaths = sum(total_deaths), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(disease_group) %>%
  mutate(proportion_of_deaths = total_deaths / sum(total_deaths))%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(desc(proportion_of_deaths)) %>%
  head(4)

clean_proportion <- proportion_table %>%
  rename(`Disease Group` = disease_group,
         `Sex` = sex,
         `Total Deaths` = total_deaths,
         `Proportion of Deaths` = proportion_of_deaths) %>%
  mutate(`Proportion of Deaths` = round(`Proportion of Deaths`, 2))

5 Contribution of Specific Conditions

The next section of this report will investigate the contribution of individual diseases within each disease group towards the proportion of gendered deaths due to it.

A consistent colour theme is utilised in this analysis. Unless otherwise indicated, the pink/orange colours represent female and the light blue represents males.

5.1.1 Infectious Causes of Death by Sex

combined_infectious

The plot above shows that the key contributor to the significant disparity between males and female deaths due to infectious disease is HIV/AIDS. However, both Hepatatis B and Hepatitis C both disproportionately affect males as well. The contribution of deaths due to HIV/AIDS has significantly decreased over time (see 5.1.2), largely due to vastly improved treatments for the disease and greater awareness of risk factors surrounding it.

The root causes for Hepatitis B deaths being higher for males than females are not perfectly understood, but it is believed to be multi-factorial, with the latest research suggesting a hormonal mechanism linking the development of hepatocellular carcinoma (a malignant tumor resulting from acute hepatitis B) with testosterone levels (Hamidu et al.2021). Conversely, oestrogen is thought to provide a protective mechanism against acute liver damage resulting from Hepatitis C infection, and is considered to be the main reason that female deaths are lower than male deaths for this disease (Baden et al.2014).

5.1.2 Change in Deaths due to HIV/AIDS and Hepatitis B/C Over Time

infectious_time

Figure 3 demonstrates the trend over time for deaths due to these 3 key diseases. HIV/AIDS treatment and preventative medicine has significantly reduced deaths due to the disease, Hepatitis C has had a highly effective cure available since 2011 (Hu et al.2020) while Hepatitis B as of yet has no effective cure.

5.2 Neurological Conditions

The top neurological conditions that lead Australia in terms of total deaths are: Dementia, epilepsy and multiple sclerosis. Of these diseases, dementia causes the most deaths by a large margin, and significantly more deaths in males than females. Roughly two-thirds of diagnosed cases of dementia and alzheimers are women (Beam et al., 2018), which aligns almost perfectly with data presented below, where two thirds of deaths due to dementia are female. This is largely due to the increased life expectancy of women, where men typically die from other causes before they die of dementia.

There is also a significant gender disparity between men and women in deaths due to multiple sclerosis. Multiple sclerosis is an autoimmune condition, and women have a much higher prevalence of auto-immune conditions. While the precise mechanism is unknown and potentially differs on a case-by-case basis, one potential explanation is that there is a greater potential for harmful mutations to emerge by virtue of having two X chromosomes, as the X chromosome contains many immune-related genes (Angum et al., 2020).

# Define dual transformation function for reverse and log10 axis # Credit to chat GPT
reverse_log_trans <- function(base = 10) {
  trans <- log_trans(base = base)
  trans_new(
    name = paste0("reverselog-", base),
    transform = function(x) -trans$transform(x),
    inverse = function(x) trans$inverse(-x),
    breaks = trans$breaks,
    format = trans$format)}

5.3 Musculoskeletal Disorders

Musculoskeletal conditions that have substantially greater impact on women than on men are rheumatoid arthritis and osteoarthritis. Similarly to multiple sclerosis discussed in the previous disease group, both of these conditions are autoimmune disorders and are therefore more likely to occur in women than in men. The mortality of gout does appear to be greater in males, but due to the relatively low number of cases this will not be explored here.

5.4 Gastrointestinal Disorders

Chronic liver disease causes more than twice as many deaths in men as it does in women, while the other leading causes of death are relatively even. Chronic liver disease as a category contains a number of conditions that can lead to early death and the mechanisms that underpin why this difference is so pronounced depends on the specific type of liver disease in question. In some cases higher oestrogen levels in women provides protection against the liver damage that results from Hepatitis C infection (Baden et al,. 2014), men are typically more likely to drink excessively throughout their life which is a significant risk factor for liver damage and lastly, there are thought to be additional as of yet not well understood hormonal mechanisms that contribute to this disparity (Cooper et al., 2023).

7 Contribution of Risk Factors

The following plots illustrate the relative contribution of specific risk factors to total deaths resulting from diseases with gender disparities.

7.1 Infectious Diseases

risk_infect <- riskxdis_byage %>%

Leading risk factors that contribute to deaths from HIV/AIDS, hepatitis C and hepatitis B are unsafe injecting practices and unsafe sex. Unsafe sex is implicated in 25% of all deaths from HIV/AIDS in men and 27% of deaths in women while unsafe injecting practices are implicated in 24% of Hepatitis C related deaths in men and 23% in women. Lastly, in men, 12% of Hepatitis B related deaths can also be attributed to unsafe injecting practices.

7.3 Musculoskeletal Conditions

As both rheumatoid and osteoarthritis are autoimmune conditions, there are few lifestyle related risk factors which contribute to deaths. That being said, there is a small contribution from tobacco use with 3% of deaths due to these conditions in men and 2% of deaths in women being attributable to tobacco use. This is consistent with MS, so there appears to be an interaction between tobacco use and additional morbidity due to autoimmune conditions.

8 Appendix

A chi-squared test of independence was conducted on the initial aggregation (p = <0.00001), and ascertained that gender was independent of disease group. This difference encouraged me to investigate each disease group separately, and I selected those disease groups which were clearly disproportionately affecting one gender over another (greater than 1000 deaths total to avoid the proportion being statistical noise, and greater than 60% of deaths affecting one gender).

Determining which diseases were responsible for the gender difference was done through visual inspection of plots and numerical comparison of absolute numbers. Generally, a proportion of >60% was roughly followed here as well.

Heatmaps were used to visualise the effect of age and risk factors on the individual diseases identified earlier. Thresholds for annotation with geom_text were determined based on visual inspection of the data to ensure that top values and any other values of interest were included in the plot.
